      "content": "Douglas N. Walton advances a nuanced perspective that suggests negotiation and regulatory activities can be philosophically justifiable on grounds of public interest—a threat to the predominant libertarian view. According to Walton, unless parties have chosen to limit a certain area of their individual freedom (for example, in regards to speech), individuals aren't coerced, and genuine free speech thrives under the voluntary authority of their own institutions.\n\n\nWarner and his libertarian comrades may yet find a crack in this seemingly unassailable fortress. Contracts penned in cyberspace, much like those in the physical world, theoretically could include terms forbidding certain laws from being applicable. Such contracts, however, carry moral (and to some, philosophical) weight only if they are entered freely and uncoerced.\n\n\nIn an anarchistic landscape, it is conceivable—although hypothetical at this stage—that voluntary municipal networks could administer certain non-coercive rules. Divergent communities could come to selective agreements to manage aspects of digital communication and behavior without invoking statist rationale. Still, these situations remain theoretical and contentious, based on the foundational libertarian premise of a state-less environment where only envied, freely chosen regulations hold sanctity.",
